org.apache.hadoop.hive.serde2

Interface Deserializer

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractDeserializer, AbstractEncodingAwareSerDe, AbstractSerDe, AccumuloSerDe, ArrowColumnarBatchSerDe, AvroSerDe, BinarySortableSerDe, BinarySortableSerDeWithEndPrefix, ByteStreamTypedSerDe, ColumnarSerDe, ColumnarSerDeBase, DelimitedJSONSerDe, DruidSerDe, DynamicSerDe, HBaseSerDe, HCatRecordSerDe, JdbcSerDe, JsonSerDe, JsonSerDe, LazyBinaryColumnarSerDe, LazyBinarySerDe, LazyBinarySerDe2, LazySimpleSerDe, MetadataTypedColumnsetSerDe, MultiDelimitSerDe, NullStructSerDe, OpenCSVSerde, OrcSerde, ParquetHiveSerDe, RegexSerDe, RegexSerDe, S3LogDeserializer, ThriftByteStreamTypedSerDe, ThriftDeserializer, ThriftJDBCBinarySerDe, TypedBytesSerDe, TypedSerDe, VectorizedOrcSerde, VectorizedSerde

    public interface Deserializer
    HiveDeserializer is used to deserialize the data from hadoop Writable to a custom java object that can be of any type that the developer wants. HiveDeserializer also provides the ObjectInspector which can be used to inspect the internal structure of the object (that is returned by deserialize function). All deserializers should extend the abstract class AbstractDeserializer. The interface is necessary for SerDes to be able to implement both Serializer and Deserializer.

      • deserialize

        Object deserialize(org.apache.hadoop.io.Writable blob)
            throws SerDeException
        Deserialize an object out of a Writable blob. In most cases, the return value of this function will be constant since the function will reuse the returned object. If the client wants to keep a copy of the object, the client needs to clone the returned deserialized value by calling ObjectInspectorUtils.getStandardObject().
        Parameters:
        blob - The Writable object containing a serialized object
        Returns:
        A Java object representing the contents in the blob.
        Throws:
        SerDeException
